We want to find the smallest k such that

\begin{align*}
\left| \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^3} - \sum_{n=1}^k \frac{1}{n^3} \right| \leq \frac{1}{20000}.
\end{align*}

Or, equivalently,

\begin{align*}
\left| \sum_{n=k +1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^3} \right| \leq \frac{1}{20000}.
\end{align*}

Interpret this sum as a Riemann sum of a certain integral that you can
compute.

sols_latex:
We want to find the smallest k such that

\begin{align*}
\left| \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^3} - \sum_{n=1}^k \frac{1}{n^3} \right| \leq \frac{1}{20000}.
\end{align*}

Or, equivalently,

\begin{align*}
\left| \sum_{n=k +1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^3} \right| \leq \frac{1}{20000}.
\end{align*}

Since all of the terms in the sum are positive, the sum itself is
positive. So, the absolute value signs are unnecessary. Note that

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=k +1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^3}
\end{align*}

can be interpreted as the right Riemann sum for the integral

\begin{align*}
\int_k^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^3} dx.
\end{align*}

Since $1/x^3$ is monotonically decreasing, the right Riemann sum is an
underestimation for the area under the curve. As step size for the
Riemann sum $\Delta x = 1$ is used.

Therefore, we have

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=k +1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^3} < \int_k^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^3} dx,
\end{align*}

and hence it suffices to find the minimal value of $k$ such that the
integral above is $\leq$ 20,000.

But the integral

\begin{align*}
\int_{k}^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^3} dx = \left[- \frac{1}{2x^2} \right]_k^{\infty} = \frac{1}{2 k ^2}.
\end{align*}

Hence

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=k+1}^\infty \frac1{n^3} < \int_k^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^3} dx = \frac{1}{2 k^2} \leq \frac{1}{20000}.
\end{align*}

The minimal such $k$ is $k=100$ (in fact, for this choice of $k$, the
right $\leq$ becomes an $=$).

Therefore we must take the first 100 terms of the sum for the
approximation to be accurate to within 1/20000.

